\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:TMS"

\end_inset

Transcranial magnetic stimulation (TMS)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
technical description
\end_layout

\end_inset

In Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (TMS), a brief (0.2 ms) and powerful
 (0.2-4.0 T) magnetic pulse is generated by the coil.
 The coil is excited by the pulsing electric current, that reaches its maximal
 intensity within 0.1-0.2 ms and then decreases to zero during next 0.5-1 ms.
 Rapid ramping of the magnetic flux leads to formation of an eddy currents
 in the conductive sections of the tissue.
 Eddy currents flow in closed loops in planes perpendicular to the magnetic
 field.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
definition of the dose
\end_layout

\end_inset

Due to the principle of induction of the electric field in the tissue, the
 stimulating magnetic field can be effectively applied only within pulses.
 The pulse ramp rate and the peak intensity are the main parameters affecting
 the unit dose of the stimulation.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Peterchev2012"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
effects in tissue
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
sub-division
\end_layout

\end_inset

Stimulation using rhythmic trains of magnetic pulses with repetition rate
 up to 100 Hz is referred as a 
\emph on
repetitive TMS
\emph default
 (
\emph on
rTMS
\emph default
).
 Different repetition rates have distinct effects on brain activity.
 TMS, in which single pulses are used instead of trains of pulses, is sometimes
 referred to as a 
\emph on
single-pulse TMS
\emph default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:single-pulse-TMS"

\end_inset

Single-pulse TMS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This technique has been developed as a diagnostic method for evaluation
 of cortico-spinal pathway.
 During stimulation of the motor cortex with single magnetic pulses of sufficien
t intensity an acute depolarisation of whole population of neurons occurs.
 It is followed by excitation of neuronal pathways from brain through the
 spinal cord to the muscles, resulting in measurable motor evoked potentials
 (MEP).
 This technique has been also used for evaluation of changes in excitability
 of cortical neurons resulting from application of different transcranial
 stimulation methods.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:rTMS"

\end_inset

Repetitive TMS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although single-pulse TMS has been developed as a diagnostic tool, it has
 been observed that the magnetic pulses have an long term neuromodulation
 effect.
 This lead to a development of more powerful TMS generators capable of delivery
 of multiple pulses within short time -- the rTMS.
 Empirically, rTMS has been further subdivided to low- (rates below 1 Hz)
 and high-frequency (rates above 5 Hz) rTMS.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Experimental evidence has revealed that rTMS with repetition rates below
 1 Hz causes cortical inhibition and on the other hand rTMS trains above
 5 Hz have opposite effect.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to increase efficiency of the high-frequency rTMS a repeated individual
 pulses have been substituted with groups of pulses, or — the burts.
 In a variant of rTMS, a theta-burst stimulation (TBS), the bursts of two
 or more pulses with intra-burst rate up to 50 Hz and inter-burst frequency
 of approximately 5 Hz are used.
 Although there is an evidence about increased efficiency, concerns about
 safety of the method arose.
 One of the limitations of current technology is that rTMS does not affect
 the deeper structures of the brain, but it is known that rTMS significantly
 involved in changing the perception of pain.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to recent studies
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Rokyta2014"

\end_inset

, this method is able to induce changes in the central nervous system at
 the cellular level including changes at ionic and metabolic level.
 Therapeutic effects were confirmed in the literature of psychiatric disorders
 such as depression, acute mania, bipolar disorder, panic attacks, hallucination
s, obsessive states, schizophrenia, catatonia or post-traumatic stress disorder
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Rokyta2012b"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:TES"

\end_inset

Transcranial electric stimulation (tES)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While in TMS the electric current is induced in the conductive parts of
 the tissue using external and rapidly changing magnetic field, in tES a
 weak electric current (0.1~2.0 mA) is applied on scalp using electrodes and
 flows through the tissue.
 The current flow in not homogenous and has variability among the affected
 tissue.
 The most of the current is conducted by surface layers (skin) and only
 small portion penetrates cortex.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on time course of the electric current, tES can be divided to 
\emph on
transcranial direct current stimulation
\emph default
 (
\emph on
tDCS
\emph default
), 
\emph on
transcranial alternating current stimulation
\emph default
 (
\emph on
tACS
\emph default
), 
\emph on
transcranial random noise stimulation
\emph default
 (
\emph on
tRNS
\emph default
) and 
\emph on
transcranial pulsed current stimulation
\emph default
 (
\emph on
tPCS
\emph default
) (for reviews see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Paulus2011a,Guleyupoglu2013a"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Electrode area and placement are important attributes.
 Area of the electrode must be chosen in accordance to the density and time
 course of the current to avoid pathological changes in the tissue.
 In order to decrease current spatial variability, multiple electrodes of
 same polarity can be placed in circular shape around one electrode of other
 polarity.
 This has been used to enhance focality of tDCS and it is denoted as 
\emph on
high-definition tDCS
\emph default
 (
\emph on
HD-tDCS
\emph default
) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Caparelli-Daquer2012a"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
tDCS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In tDCS a direct current with intensity of 0.4-2 mA is applied on scalp via
 electrode pads for 5~30 minutes.
 Current causes most of the changes right under the electrodes: under cathode
 it decreases excitability of cortical neurons and under the anode the effect
 is opposite.
 By changing the area of the electrodes a current density can be changed
 and thus the effect of the stimulation.
 The effects last for few hours after the stimulation ends as in TMS.
 In clinical use, tDCS is considered as a noninvasive stimulation that is
 affordable and easy to use compare to other neuromodulatory techniques.
 TDCS is a promising method for the treatment of chronic pain 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "OConnell2014"

\end_inset

, as well as for patients with neuropsychiatric diseases and other neurological
 disorders 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kuo2014"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Novel approaches (tACS, tPCS, tRNS)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
About novel approaches of transcranial electric stimulation is not known
 too much.
 In 
\emph on
transcranial alternating current stimulation
\emph default
 (
\emph on
tACS
\emph default
) an oscillatory electric current is delivered to the cortical tissue with
 oscillation frequency between 0.1-5000 Hz.
 It is thought that the tACS signal interacts with ongoing cortical oscillations
 and induce changes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Antal2013"

\end_inset

.
 Another method, 
\emph on
transcranial pulse current stimulation
\emph default
 (
\emph on
tPCS
\emph default
), is a variation of tACS where the harmonic current is exchanged for the
 rectangular electric signal.
 Though the spectra in tPCS is wider, the dominant frequency is still the
 baseline frequency of the pulses.
 Recently, interest has emerged in new stimulation method, transcranial
 random noise stimulation (tRNS) in which a random noise signal is applied
 with the frequency spectrum normaly distributed over given frequency range.
 tRNS is usually divided to low- (0.1-100 Hz) and high-frequency tRNS (100-640
 Hz) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Terney2008"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Numerical simulations of electromagnetic field distribution in human cranium
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It has been presented 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Wagner2004,Golestanirad2010,Tsuyama2009,March2014,Datta2009,Bikson2012,Bikson2012a,Caparelli-Daquer2012a,Kuo2013b"

\end_inset

 that numerical electromagnetic (EM) simulations (solving Maxwell’s equations)
 are powerful tools for estimation of distribution of magnetic and electric
 field induced by transcranial stimulation (TS) inside the human head.
 From distribution of magnetic and electric field electrical current density
 distribution can be computed.
 Most numerical simulations used for modeling of TS are based on finite
 element method (FEM).
 In literature some simplifications of realistic model of human head were
 used.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Wagner2004"

\end_inset

 FEM is used to evaluate the induced electric current density in simplified
 model, head was approximated by a sphere, exposed by a time varying magnetic
 field.
 A more accurate prediction of the field distribution can be found in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Golestanirad2010,Datta2009,Bikson2012,Bikson2012a"

\end_inset

, where different 3-D patient specific numerical head phantoms (anatomically
 accurate numerical head models) have been developed.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Golestanirad2010"

\end_inset

 the phantoms were created using head imaging data of individual patients.
 The simulations were performed with relatively course mesh and difference
 between electrical properties of cerebrospinal fluid and brain white/gray
 matter was neglected.
 The side effect of TS therapy in form of temperature increase was published
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "March2014"

\end_inset

.
 Improvements in coil performance would have a signiﬁcant impact in extending
 the usefulness of TS in clinical applications 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Tsuyama2009"

\end_inset

.
 New design and optimization of coil for the treatment optimization in sense
 of ability to stimulate the brain at depth and with high spatial locality,
 was described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Tsuyama2009"

\end_inset

.
 Also the electrode placement has been studied and 4x1 ring electrode assembly
 has been proposed to increase focality of the stimulation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Datta2009,Caparelli-Daquer2012a,Edwards2013"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Brain network dynamics, functional mapping and stimulation protocols
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Stimulation protocols used for theraphy neglect the dynamic nature of brain
 networks.
 Althought in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Price2010"

\end_inset

 the backgroud EEG activity is used to determine timing to improve efficiacy
 rTMS, more studies ought to be carried out.
 Incorporating the network dynamics and functional connections into stimulation
 protocols can be promising especially in methods that interact with ongoing
 neuronal activity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The methods of transcranial stimulation are used to modulate cortical activity
 for diagnostic and treatment.
 Focal inhibition or excitation of cortical neurons vs.
 to pharmacological treatment vs.
 invasive stimulation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The treatment follows simple stimulation protocols, that are mostly based
 on empirical knowledge.
 In recent studies the parameters of the stimulation (placement and shape
 of the electrodes, coils, parameters of the electromagnetic field) has
 been manipulated based on simulation of the field in the tissue.
 Also the timing of the stimulation based on background EEG activity has
 been investigated as a mean of eficiacy increase.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Models ignore the orientation of the neurons.
 The orientation of the neurons in external field may be inportant (proof
 need).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Functional mapping can reveal new areas for stimulation.
 Also connectivity of cortical cores can reveal a sequence of pulses in
 different regions are needed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The ongoing activity can be mapped by LORETA and the stimulation can be
 controlled.
\end_layout

